vectorData.altText: 13. Within the dorsal columns of the spinal cord, the fasciculus gracilis is _______________ to the fasciculus cuneatus.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

That’s right!  The fasciculus gracilis is medial to the fasciculus cuneatus. This is because the fasciculus cuneatus contains primary sensory axons from the upper body, which are added to the lateral aspect of DC.
Dorsal view of the cervical spinal cord. From Neuroanatomy: An Atlas of Structures, Sections, and Systems, 7th ed., by Duane E. Haines, © 2007

Identify the dorsal columns of white matter in this image. As you know, they lie between the dorsal median sulcus and the dorsal lateral sulcus. Note, however, that at this level, a third sulcus subdivides the dorsal column into the fasciculus gracilis (more medial) and the fasciculus cuneatus (more lateral).
Both of these tracts carry fine touch, vibration sense and conscious proprioception from the ipsilateral body. The difference is in the body region.
The fasciculus gracilis carries these sensations from the lower body, inc. the leg. It is therefore present in the dorsal column throughout the length of the spinal cord.

The fasciculus cuneatus carries these sensations from the upper body, inc. the arm. It is therefore present in the dorsal column only at upper thoracic and cervical levels.
We’ll start with the lower body.
